The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	London: South Africa coach Mickey Arthur has emerged as a surprise candidate to be the next England coach, while Ashley Giles has been told he is not in the frame.     
	Sources suggest Arthur is the external candidate most favoured by the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB), who had hoped to appoint a replacement for Peter Moores before the start of the summer.        
	London: Indian Premier League (IPL) franchise Rajasthan Royals are in line for a nomination in the World Team of the Year category 2008 at the Laureus World Sports Awards. Led by Australian leg-spin legend Shane Warne, the Royals began as underdogs but ran away with the top prize in the inaugural IPL Twenty20 tournament last May.        
	Lahore: Police arrested Pakistan fielding coach Ijaz Ahmed on Thursday over an alleged land scam. The 40-year-old former Test cricketer is accused of writing checks to two property dealers that bounced.          
	New Delhi: Rohan Bopanna and Aisam-ul Haq Qureshi advanced to the doubles quarter finals of the $50,000 Korat Open after a 6-4, 6-1 win over the Thai pair of Pongsatorr Benjamas and Prach Mahathavorn in the first round. They next take on the Indian pair of Ashutosh Singh and Purav Raja, who defeated the French duo Mathieu Montcourt and Edouarc Roger-Vasselin 6-3, 6-3 in the opening round.        
	Bree (Belgium): Kim Clijsters is returning to the tennis circuit after two years in retirement. Clijsters announced her comeback at the tennis facility in Bree, Belgium, where she has been practising recently.          
	Shenzhen: Holder Rashid Khan and fellow Indian Amanjyot Singh carded an even par 72 each in the under-18 section of the Faldo Series Asia Grand Final at the Mission Hills Golf Club. The duo is three shots behind overall leader Hsieh Yu-Ling, a 17-year-old woman golfer from Chinese Taipei. Gauri Monga shot an 81 in Girls Under-16.        
	Teresopolis (Brazil): Peles reported remarks suggesting that Brazil forward Robinho took drugs were a misunderstanding, both men said on Wednesday. Maybe theres been a misunderstanding because I didnt say that at all, maybe they took him the wrong information, Pele said in comments broadcast on Brazilian television. Robinho said at Brazils training camp: I think it was a misunderstanding, Pele made a mistake but I dont have any bad feelings against him.          
	Austin: Lance Armstrong expects to be back on his bike in days after surgery on his broken collarbone on Wednesday. Surgeon Doug Elenz inserted a stainless steel plate and 12 screws to stabilise the broken collarbone two days after Armstrong crashed in the first stage of the Vuelta of Castilla and Leon in northern Spain.      
